Obviously, $a_{1}=1$ or $a_{2}=1$. Now consider the integer $m$, and let $m$ have $k$ distinct prime factors. We will prove by induction on $k$ that $m$ appears in the sequence $\left\{a_{n}ight\}$. Let $S_{n}=a_{1}+a_{2}+\cdots+a_{n}, n \geqslant 1$. For $k=1$, $m$ is a power of a prime, say $m=p^{\alpha}$, where $\alpha>0$ and $p$ is a prime.
Assume $m$ does not appear in the sequence $\left\{a_{n}ight\}$. Since the terms in the sequence $\left\{a_{n}ight\}$ are distinct, there exists a positive integer $N$ such that for all $n \geqslant N$, we have $a_{n}>p^{\alpha}$.
If for some $n \geqslant N, p 
mid S_{n}$, then $p^{\alpha}$ and $S_{n}$ are coprime. Since $a_{1}, a_{2}, \cdots, a_{n}$ do not contain $p^{\alpha}$, by the definition of the sequence $\left\{a_{n}ight\}$, we have $a_{n+1} \leqslant p^{\alpha}$, which contradicts $a_{n+1}>p^{\alpha}$.
Thus, for each $n \geqslant N$, we have $p \mid S_{n}$. Therefore, $p\left|S_{n}, pight| S_{n+1} \Rightarrow p \mid a_{n+1} \Rightarrow a_{n+1}$ and $S_{n+1}$ are not coprime, which contradicts the definition of $a_{n+1}$.
Assume $k \geqslant 2$, and the conclusion holds for $k-1$. Let $m=p_{1}^{\alpha_{1}} p_{2}^{\alpha_{2}} p_{k-1}^{\alpha_{k-1}} p_{k}^{\alpha_{k}}$. Assume $m$ does not appear in the sequence $\left\{a_{n}ight\}$. Then there exists a positive integer $N^{\prime}$ such that for all $n \geqslant N^{\prime}$, we have $a_{n}>m$.
Choose sufficiently large positive integers $ eta_{1},  eta_{2}, \cdots,  eta_{k-1}$, such that $M=p_{1}^{ eta_{1}} p_{2}^{ eta_{2}} p_{k-1}^{ eta_{k-1}}>\max _{1 \leqslant n \leqslant N^{\prime}} a_{n}$.
We will prove: for $n>N^{\prime}$, we have $a_{n+1} 
eq M$.
For any $n>N^{\prime}$, if $S_{n}$ is coprime with $p_{1} p_{2} \cdots p_{k}$, then $m$ and $S_{n}$ are coprime. Since $a_{1}, a_{2}, \cdots, a_{n}$ do not contain $m$, and $a_{n+1}>m$, this contradicts the definition of $a_{n+1}$. Therefore, for any $n>N^{\prime}$, $S_{n}$ is not coprime with $p_{1} p_{2} \cdots p_{k}$.
Case 1: If there exists $i(1 \leqslant i \leqslant k-1)$ such that $p_{i} \mid S_{n}$, then by $\left(a_{n+1}, S_{n}ight)=1 \Rightarrow p_{i} 
mid a_{n+1}$, and $p_{i} \mid M$, thus $a_{n+1} 
eq M$;
Case 2: If for each $i(1 \leqslant i \leqslant k-1)$, we have $p_{i} 
mid S_{n}$, then by $(*)$ we know $p_{k} \mid S_{n}$, by $\left(a_{n+1}, S_{n}ight)=1 \Rightarrow p_{k} 
mid a_{n+1} \Rightarrow p_{k} 
mid S_{k}+a_{n+1}=S_{n+1}$. Again by $(*)$ we know there exists $i_{0}\left(1 \leqslant i_{0} \leqslant k-1ight)$ such that $p_{i_{0}} \mid S_{n+1}$, thus $p_{i_{0}} 
mid S_{n} \Rightarrow p_{i_{0}} 
mid a_{n+1} \Rightarrow a_{n+1} 
eq M$. Therefore, for $n \geqslant N^{\prime}+1$, we have $a_{n+1} 
eq M$, and $M>\max _{1 \leqslant n \leqslant N^{\prime}} a_{n}$, i.e., $M$ does not appear in the sequence $\left\{a_{n}ight\}$, which contradicts the induction hypothesis. Thus, if $m$ has $k$ distinct prime factors, then $m$ must appear in the sequence $\left\{a_{n}ight\}$.
